Thanks, I had already verified, that the patches applied cleanly
to both 2007-11-21 and 2007-11-29. The next snapshot will contain
part of the patches I submitted (since they also went into the
SIPp repository), you may wait for it to appear, e.g.:

Index: message.cpp
===================================================================
--- message.cpp (revision 346)
+++ message.cpp (working copy)
@@ -318,9 +318,9 @@
        method = NULL;
     } else {
       if (p != method) {
-       memmove(method, p, strlen(p));
+       memmove(method, p, strlen(p) + 1);
       }
-      method = (char *)realloc(method, strlen(method));
+      method = (char *)realloc(method, strlen(method) + 1);
       if (!method) { ERROR("Out of memory"); }
       ack = (!strcmp(method, "ACK"));
       cancel = (!strcmp(method, "CANCEL"));
@@ -332,6 +332,7 @@
   for (int i = 0; i < numComponents(); i++) {
     freeMessageComponent(messageComponents[i]);
   }
+  free(method);
 }

This fixes the string length in memmove() and also the memory leak
I found when I searched for the bug that caused garbled output (and
which was caused by that short memmove ...)

The following two chunks will not become part of the snapshot and
will only be in the next stable release, but it does fix a problem
observed in my tests with SIPp (keyb-thread() runs in tighjt loop
if sipp is started from a shell script without -bg as a background
program):

Index: screen.cpp
===================================================================
--- screen.cpp  (revision 346)
+++ screen.cpp  (working copy)
@@ -58,9 +58,15 @@
   gettimeofday (clock, &tzp); \
 }

-int  screen_readkey()
+/* ERR is actually -1, but this prevents us from needing to use curses.h in
+ * sipp.cpp. */
+int screen_readkey()
 {
-  return getch();
+  int c = getch();
+  if (c == ERR) {
+    return -1;
+  }
+  return c;
 }

 void screen_exit(int rc)
Index: sipp.cpp
===================================================================
--- sipp.cpp    (revision 346)
+++ sipp.cpp    (working copy)
@@ -1420,6 +1420,9 @@

   while(!feof(stdin)){
     c = screen_readkey();
+    if (c == -1) {
+       return;
+    }
     if (process_key(c)) {
        return;
     }

I'll give this patch (from Charles P Wright) some local testing
and if it does not cause any problems; I'd like to see it added
to the port ...

Regards, STefan
